<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06143207 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06143207 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CONSUMER; PET  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  PARTY animals are embraced by hostess Rosanne Marcus, who arms herself with aPooper Scooper when guests arrive and warns two-legged masters to watch theirstep and avoid heavy petting.;    Pet lovers are paying $200, plus $6.50 andup for each pet, to throw birthday parties for pooches in what has blossomedinto another Southern California ritual. These are yuppies' puppies.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BIRTHDAY HOSTESS HELPS PUT ON THE DOG  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Consumer  </MEMO><TEXT>     Marcus, 34, of suburban Encino greets each arriving canine with a Milk Boneparty favor, snaps a party hat over its head and organizes a &quot;bury the bone&quot;contest.;    &quot;We think it will go over big. People love to have parties, andthe people that have these parties are real animal lovers. Otherwise, theywould think it was the stupidest thing they ever heard of,&quot; Marcus said.;   The main attraction in the balloon-festooned Marcus yard is a long sheet ofbutcher paper marked with paw prints to signify where each dog should sit forkibble or bits-o-hamburger. Canine popcorn and dog sunglasses are sometimesincluded, depending on the owner's pocketbook.;    &quot;Only in L.A.,&quot; said JudyGregg, who was on hand for a recent party celebrating the birth of Lady.;   Marcus threw her first birthday party a year ago after seeing people in theLaurel Canyon dog park singing &quot;Happy Birthday&quot; to a mutt. That firstmemorable party was for Buffie, a cocker spaniel owned by Marcus.;    Nineteendogs showed up for the shindig, and it was a howling success. A short timelater she went into business as &quot;The Party Animals.&quot;;    Keeping the peace issometimes a challenge, she confesses, recalling the boorish behavior of onerecent party guest named Schultzie, a schnauzer that urinated on several petowners.;    &quot;I had all these people coming up and saying, 'This dog peed onme,' &quot; Marcus said.;    At another four-legged event, one owner insisted thateverything be done in turquoise because it was her dog's favorite color. Sheexplained the dog favored a turquoise chair at home. No mention was made thatdogs are said to be color-blind.;    The owner of a Lhasa apso named Nanuasked that Marcus supply Hershey's chocolate kisses for her dog. Marcus notedchocolate wasn't good for dogs, but the owner insisted, so a cake in the shapeof a giant chocolate kiss was provided.;    &quot;Other times we've taken her outto McDonald's for a hamburger for her birthday. She's our baby,&quot; said Nanu'sowner, 69-year-old Rose Casabianca of Tujunga.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910522  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  414  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 22, 199100143207,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>